hook.real_world_problem:
You've written a CSV parser. Does it handle quoted commas? Empty fields? Escaped double-quotes? You run the program, look at the output, think 'looks right' — and ship it.

Three weeks later, a seller uploads a product named `"Dell 27", Monitor` and the whole import crashes. The bug was there the whole time, you just didn't test those cases.

**The professional solution:**
```java
@Test
void parsesQuotedFieldWithComma() {
    List<String> cols = parseCSVLine('"Dell 27, Monitor",18999');
    assertEquals(2, cols.size());
    assertEquals("Dell 27, Monitor", cols.get(0));
    assertEquals("18999", cols.get(1));
}

@Test
void handlesEscapedQuote() {
    List<String> cols = parseCSVLine('"Dell 27\"\" Monitor",18999');
    assertEquals("Dell 27\" Monitor", cols.get(0));
}

@Test
void emptyFieldReturnsEmptyString() {
    List<String> cols = parseCSVLine("Mouse,,799");
    assertEquals("", cols.get(1));
}
```

These 3 tests run in milliseconds. If your code breaks, they scream immediately — before you ship, before a seller notices, before data gets corrupted.

JUnit 5 is the standard Java testing framework. Built into Maven and Gradle. Integrated into every IDE. The tool every Java developer uses every day.

concept_explanation.junit5_setup:
**JUnit 5 setup — Maven dependency:**

```xml
<!-- pom.xml -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
    <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
    <version>5.10.0</version>
    <scope>test</scope>
</dependency>
```

**Test class structure:**
```java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.*;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;

class CalculatorTest {   // no 'public' required in JUnit 5; class name: [Class]Test

    @Test
    void addsTwoPositiveNumbers() {  // no 'public', no return type
        // Arrange (set up)
        Calculator calc = new Calculator();
        // Act (call the method)
        int result = calc.add(3, 4);
        // Assert (verify)
        assertEquals(7, result);
    }
}
```

**Convention**: test classes in `src/test/java` mirroring the source package structure. Test class named `[ClassUnderTest]Test`.

concept_explanation.basic_assertions:
**JUnit 5 Assertions — the most common:**

```java
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;

// assertEquals: most common — checks exact equality
assertEquals(7,         calc.add(3, 4));
assertEquals("HELLO",   "hello".toUpperCase());
assertEquals(3.0,       Math.sqrt(9.0), 0.001);  // double: allow delta

// assertTrue / assertFalse:
assertTrue("Hyderabad".startsWith("Hyd"));
assertFalse(list.isEmpty());
assertTrue(price > 0, "Price must be positive");  // custom failure message

// assertNull / assertNotNull:
assertNull(result);          // must be null
assertNotNull(user);         // must not be null
assertNotNull(user.getId(), "User ID should be set after save");

// assertThrows — test that an exception is thrown:
IllegalArgumentException ex = assertThrows(
    IllegalArgumentException.class,
    () -> account.withdraw(-100));
assertEquals("Amount must be positive", ex.getMessage());

// Multiple assertions in one test:
assertAll(
    () -> assertEquals("Aisha", user.getName()),
    () -> assertEquals(28, user.getAge()),
    () -> assertEquals("Hyderabad", user.getCity())
);
```

concept_explanation.lifecycle_annotations:
**JUnit 5 lifecycle annotations:**

```java
class BankAccountTest {
    BankAccount account;  // shared test fixture

    @BeforeEach           // runs BEFORE each @Test method
    void setUp() {
        account = new BankAccount("ACC-001", 1000.0);
    }

    @AfterEach            // runs AFTER each @Test method
    void tearDown() {
        account.close();
    }

    @BeforeAll            // runs ONCE before all tests in the class (must be static)
    static void initDatabase() {
        System.out.println("Setting up test database...");
    }

    @AfterAll             // runs ONCE after all tests (must be static)
    static void cleanupDatabase() {
        System.out.println("Tearing down test database...");
    }

    @Test
    void depositIncreasesBalance() {
        account.deposit(500);            // uses account from @BeforeEach
        assertEquals(1500, account.getBalance());
    }

    @Test
    void withdrawReducesBalance() {
        account.withdraw(200);           // fresh account from @BeforeEach
        assertEquals(800, account.getBalance());
    }
}
```

**Execution order per test**: @BeforeAll → [@BeforeEach → @Test → @AfterEach] × N → @AfterAll

